  "prompt": "What is Boroscopic inspection and how do you measure it?",
  "response": "Borescopic inspection (or borescope inspection) is a non-destructive testing method used to visually examine the internal surfaces of small or hard-to-reach spaces using a borescope. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\nDefinition:\n- A borescope is an optical device with a rigid or flexible tube\n- Contains a lens system and light source\n- Allows visual inspection of internal areas that are not directly visible\n\nMeasurement and Process:\n1. Equipment:\n- Borescope (rigid or flexible)\n- Light source\n- Camera/video recording capabilities\n- Monitor or viewing screen\n\n2. Measurement Techniques:\n- Visual assessment of internal surfaces\n- Capturing images/videos\n- Measuring dimensions using built-in measurement tools\n- Comparing findings against predetermined standards\n\n3. Common Applications:\n- Aircraft engine inspections\n- Automotive engine diagnostics\n- Industrial machinery maintenance\n- Pipe and tube inspections\n- Structural/architectural evaluations\n\n4. Measurement Parameters:\n- Surface condition\n- Corrosion levels\n- Crack detection\n- Material integrity\n- Dimensional accuracy\n\n5. Types of Borescopes:\n- Rigid borescopes\n- Flexible borescopes\n- Video borescopes\n- Fiberscope varieties\n\nEach type has specific measurement capabilities and applications.",
